<h2 id="working-buffer-protocol--new">Working Buffer Protocol ‚≠ź NEW</h2>

<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Capture EVERY exchange in the danger zone between memory flush and compaction.</p>

<h3 id="how-it-works">How It Works</h3>

<ol>
  <li><strong>At 60% context</strong> (check via <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">session_status</code>): CLEAR the old buffer, start fresh</li>
  <li><strong>Every message after 60%</strong>: Append both human‚Äôs message AND your response summary</li>
  <li><strong>After compaction</strong>: Read the buffer FIRST, extract important context</li>
  <li><strong>Leave buffer as-is</strong> until next 60% threshold</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="buffer-format">Buffer Format</h3>

<div class="language-markdown highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="gh"># Working Buffer (Danger Zone Log)</span>
<span class="gs">**Status:**</span> ACTIVE
<span class="gs">**Started:**</span> [timestamp]
<span class="p">
---
</span>
<span class="gu">## [timestamp] Human</span>
[their message]

<span class="gu">## [timestamp] Agent (summary)</span>
[1-2 sentence summary of your response + key details]
</code></pre></div></div>

<h3 id="why-this-works-1">Why This Works</h3>

<p>The buffer is a file ‚ÄĒ it survives compaction. Even if SESSION-STATE.md wasn‚Äôt updated properly, the buffer captures everything said in the danger zone. After waking up, you review the buffer and pull out what matters.</p>

<p><strong>The rule:</strong> Once context hits 60%, EVERY exchange gets logged. No exceptions.</p>

